# Review of `app.js`: Error Handling, Input Validation & Security

The file is small (22 lines) and functional, but it has a number of gaps that would matter in any real deployment. Here's a focused review.

## 1. No error handling middleware

Express routes that throw (sync or async) will crash the process or leak stack traces. Add a catch-all error handler **after** your routes:

```js
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
});
```

Never send `err.message` or `err.stack` to the client — it leaks implementation details.

## 2. No 404 handler

Unmatched routes fall through to Express's default HTML response. Add:

```js
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' }));
```

## 3. No input validation / parsing hardening

Though the current routes don't accept input, as soon as you add `POST`/`PUT`:

- Add body parsers with **explicit size limits**: `app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }))`.
- Validate all inputs with a schema library (`zod`, `joi`, `express-validator`). Never trust `req.body`, `req.query`, or `req.params`.
- Validate `Content-Type` for write endpoints.
- Coerce and bound numeric/string inputs (length, range, allowed charset).

Example:

```js
const { z } = require('zod');
const UserQuery = z.object({ id: z.coerce.number().int().positive() });

app.get('/users/:id', (req, res, next) => {
  const parsed = UserQuery.safeParse(req.params);
  if (!parsed.success) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid id' });
  // ...
});
```

## 4. Missing security middleware

At minimum, add:

- **`helmet`** — sets `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, HSTS, CSP, etc.
- **`express-rate-limit`** — prevent brute force / DoS on `/users`, auth endpoints.
- **`cors`** with an explicit allowlist (never `origin: '*'` for authenticated APIs).
- Disable the `X-Powered-By` header: `app.disable('x-powered-by')`.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

## 5. PII exposure in `/users`

`/users` returns emails with no authentication or authorization. Even for demo data, this is the shape of a real vulnerability. Gate it behind auth middleware and only return fields the caller is allowed to see.

## 6. Hard-coded configuration

`app.listen(3000, …)` hard-codes the port. Use `process.env.PORT` with a sane default, and don't start the listener when the module is required by tests:

```js
const PORT = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
if (require.main === module) {
  app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
}
```

This also avoids the side-effect of starting a server every time a test imports `app.js`.

## 7. No graceful shutdown

The server ignores `SIGTERM`/`SIGINT`, so in-flight requests get dropped on deploy. Capture the `http.Server` returned by `listen()` and call `server.close()` on shutdown signals.

## 8. No logging / request tracing

`console.log` is not structured and has no request IDs. Use `pino` or `morgan` (request logs), and include a correlation ID header (`X-Request-Id`) on every response. Avoid logging request bodies for endpoints that handle secrets.

## 9. Unhandled promise rejections

Add process-level guards so a stray rejection doesn't silently degrade the server:

```js
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => { console.error(reason); });
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => { console.error(err); process.exit(1); });
```

## 10. No HTTPS / transport concerns

In production, terminate TLS at a reverse proxy (nginx, ALB, Cloudflare) and trust it explicitly: `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` — required for `express-rate-limit` and secure cookies to see the real client IP.

